	abstract = {The objective of this research is to determine the extent to which environmental, social and governance indicators can explain corporate efficiency, given by three indicators: return on assets (ROA), return on equity (ROE) and return on sales (ROS). In order to determine the validity of corporate efficiency measurement a model of three linear regressions with panel data was designed. This model tests whether the environmental (E), social performance (S) and corporate governance (G) variables of the studied companies are able to explain their profitability for the period 2014–2017. Results show that sustainable value (S) explains profitability—or return on sales (ROS)—with a high degree of significance, whereas it explains corporate efficiency to a moderate extent. Likewise, corporate governance (G) is the most significant variable for the generation of sustainable value. We conclude that generating sustainable value allows firms to meet profitability goals and to mitigate environmental and social impacts. Thus, the model is useful for measuring corporate efficiency in sustainable companies.},
